interesting, I didn&#x27;t know about that. You still end up having to do a toString override to properly suppress the &#x27;undefined&#x27; return value though:<p><pre><code>    window.__defineGetter__(&#x27;help&#x27;, function () {
        console.log(&#x27;I\&#x27;m here for you&#x27;); f = function() {}; f.toString = function() {return &quot; &quot;;}; return f;
    });
</code></pre>
But __defineGetter__ would let the execution of the command work in other places than the JS console, so that&#x27;s cool.
